Applying symbology uniformly for a layer

You can control the way layers are displayed in a ggplot map.

Required packages

This example uses the following packages:

library(tidyverse)

Sample data

Here is a map of African countries and airports, with lines representing the flights between pairs of airports.

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = countries) +
  geom_sf(data = within_africa_flows) +
  geom_sf(data = airports) +
  theme_bw()

Line symbology

I can set line weight (size =), color (color = or colour =), type (lty =), and transparency (alpha =).

Options for line types are:

  • blank
  • solid
  • dashed
  • dotted
  • dotdash
  • longdash
  • twodash
ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = countries) +
  geom_sf(data = within_africa_flows,
          color = "cornflowerblue",
          size = 0.5,
          lty = "dotted",
          alpha = 0.3) +
  geom_sf(data = airports) +
  theme_bw()

Point symbology

You can specify point shapes with any of the following numbers:

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = countries) +
  geom_sf(data = within_africa_flows,
          color = "cornflowerblue",
          size = 0.5,
          lty = "dotted",
          alpha = 0.3) +
  geom_sf(data = airports,
          shape = 3) +
  theme_bw()

You can also specify color, size, and transparency.

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = countries) +
  geom_sf(data = within_africa_flows,
          color = "cornflowerblue",
          size = 0.5,
          lty = "dotted",
          alpha = 0.3) +
  geom_sf(data = airports,
          shape = 16,
          size = 4,
          alpha = 0.3,
          color = "red") +
  theme_bw()

For shapes 21 through 25, you can specify a color and a fill color:

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = countries) +
  geom_sf(data = within_africa_flows,
          color = "cornflowerblue",
          size = 0.5,
          lty = "dotted",
          alpha = 0.3) +
  geom_sf(data = airports,
          shape = 21,
          size = 4,
          alpha = 0.3,
          color = "red",
          fill = "blue") +
  theme_bw()

Polygon symbology

For polygons, you can specify the fill color, the fill transparency, the outline color, the outline weight, and the outline line type.

ggplot(countries) +
  geom_sf(size = 1.5,
          lty = "dotted",
          color = "pink",
          fill = "yellow",
          alpha = 0.2) +
  theme_bw()

If you set color = NA you can leave off the outlines.

ggplot(countries) +
  geom_sf(color = NA,
          fill = "yellow",
          alpha = 0.2) +
  theme_bw()
